    <div id="research">
      <p class="sub-sub-title">Academic Research</p>
      <p class="date">Summer 2018</p>
      <p>The <span class="text-italic">k</span>-Regret operator is a recently invented database query that combines
         the nice properties of the well-known <span class="text-italic">top-k</span> and <span class="text-italic">skyline</span> operator to output a
         small subset of a large database that represents the items close to users' desired items,
         without any users' inputs. Currently, the existing algorithms for "k-Regret operator"
         does not have any dynamic operations for updating the result set when there is a change
         in the database (i.e. an insertion or deletion of an item).</p>
      <p>Our research focuses on creating a new algorithm that updates the result set
         previously obtained by a k-Regret operator algorithm whenever there is
         an insertion or deletion of an item in the database. Our algorithms are implemented in C++.</p>
      <p>For an in-depth explanation of the research, please refer to <a href="https://1drv.ms/b/s!Ar9GFEbmQta-alpxFtSpicUbJsg">this paper</a>.</p>
